value.value: Suppression or prevention of the carcinogenic process/development of cancer.
The use of radiation, either via external beams or small radioactive pellets, to treat a tumor in the brain.
A surgical procedure on the brain to remove a tumor.
A surgical procedure on the breast.
A plastic surgery procedure in which the eyebrows are raised on the forehead to give a more youthful appearance.

A gastrointestinal infection attributed to the bacteria campylobacter. It is usually contracted by consuming raw or undercooked poultry or consuming a food that has been in contact with raw poultry. It is characterized by abdominal pain, fever, and  diarrhea and usually resolves in two to five days.
Counseling to change behaviors that have a negative effect on an individual's cardiac system.
A surgical procedure on the heart.
A surgical procedure to remove plaque from the carotid arteries.
Orthopedic appliances designed to immobilized bones.
A surgical procedure to remove cataracts from the eyes.
A surgical procedure to remove cancer from the cervix.
The administration of drugs to ameliorate the effects of or shrink a brain tumor.
An acute diarrheal illness caused by consuming water or food contaminated by the bacterium Vibrio cholerae. Adequate rehydration is key to surviving this illness.

label.value: Chronic Kidney Disease due to Diabetes Mellitus

value.value: Longstanding kidney disease as a complication of diabetes.

label.value: Chronic Kidney Disease due to Hypertension

value.value: Longstanding kidney disease as a complication of hypertension.
Treatment to assist an individual with longstanding and constant pain.
A non-neoplastic longstanding disorder of the respiratory system.

label.value: Cirrhosis of the Liver Secondary to Hepatitis B

value.value: Cirrhosis of the liver that develops as a sequelae of a hepatitis b infection.

label.value: Cirrhosis of the Liver Secondary to Hepatitis C

value.value: Cirrhosis of the liver that develops as a sequelae of a hepatitis c infection.
The use of cocaine that results in the development of a dependency that adversely affects an individual's life.
Chemoprevention use in a clinical setting.

A two part electronic device with one part that is implanted under the skin with wires that connect to the cochlea, and an external portion that receives the sound. It is for individuals with severe hearing impairment.

A structured program that helps the patient identify and replace thoughts and behaviors that cause or worsen sleep problems with habits that promote sound sleep. Techniques include stimulus control therapy, sleep restriction, sleep hygiene, sleep environment improvement, relaxation training, remaining passively awake, and biofeedback.
A surgical procedure that lengthens the esophagus with part of the stomach to provide relief from GERD or Barrett's esophagus.
A surgical procedure in which part of the colon is removed.
Any of a number of surgical procedures that can be done on the colon, rectum and/or anus.
A disease that can be transmitted from one individual to another.
A surgical procedure in which areas of dead bone are drilled to increase blood flow, slow or stop tissue destruction and decrease pressure.
Surgery to improve the aesthetics of an individual's body.
Surgery to remove tumors that use high powered microscopes with fiberoptic illumination to identify target areas.
The use of cold to freeze heart tissue that is a source of an irregular rhythm. It is administered via a balloon catheter that use advanced radiographic techniques.
Data obtained through patient examination or treatment.
Surgery to create an eyelid fold where one does not exist.
Learning how to drive with a machine that simulates the motor vehicle of choice.
Reshaping or suturing of the ear(s) to lie flatter against the head.
A procedure to examine the elbow joint via an arthroscope.
Destruction of endometrial tissue by cold, heated fluids, microwave energy or high-energy radiofrequency.
A surgical procedure to remove or destroy cancer in the endometrium.
A surgical procedure on the nasal sinuses with an endoscope.
A surgical procedure on the gastric tract to remove deep tumors via endoscope.
The use of an endoscopic scope to visualize and treat issues in the urethra, bladder and ureter.
The repair of an aneurysm by deploying a graft into the area of the aneurysm via a special endovascular catheter.

An area of medicine that seeks to identify and treat medical disorders in humans that result from improper or inadequate diet, or from diseases that make the body unable to handle the nutrients delivered to it in the normal diet. The usual treatment is dietary, but can be the delivery of nutrients by other means. (from University of Pittsburgh Medical Center glossary)
The repair of an aneurysm by deploying a stent graft into the area of the aneurysm via a special endovascular catheter.

A pathotype of Escherichia coli, which is a gram-negative bacteria that is transmitted through the fecal-oral route. It has an incubation period of 9-12 hours and a duration of 12 days. Symptoms may include persistent severe acute diarrhea.

A pathotype of Escherichia coli, which is a gram-negative bacteria that is transmitted through the fecal-oral route. It has an incubation period of 10-72 hours and a duration of 1-5 days. Symptoms may include acute, occasionally severe diarrhea without fever.
Ablation of an area of the heart that the source of a dysrhythmia via the insertion of a catheter placed in the pericardial space.
An injection of a steroid into the epidural space, the sleeve that surrounds the spinal sac and cushions the spinal nerves and cords to reduce low back or neck pain associated with inflammation.
